  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text('About Page'),
      ),
      body: Center(
        child: Text('Welcome to about page'),
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

In this example, we have created a ResponsivePage StatefulWidget that renders either HomePage or AboutPage based on the screen size of the device. We define routes for both pages in MaterialApp, and handle navigation to these routes in the build method of ResponsivePage, based on the screen size detected by the LayoutBuilder and MediaQuery widgets.

When the screen size is greater than or equal to 600, ResponsivePage shows the HomePage, and when it is less than 600, it shows the AboutPage. This example can be extended to handle more sizes and routes according to the specific requirements of your app.

In Flutter, `final` and `late` are keywords used for variables to specify their behavior.

`final` keyword: 

- When a variable is declared as final, it can only be assigned once and then it becomes a constant.
- A final variable must be initialized at the time of declaration or in a constructor.

Here's an example:

```dart
final int myNumber = 5;
final String myName = 'John';
final List<String> myNames = ['John', 'Mary', 'Jane'];
```

`late` keyword:

- When a variable is declared as late, it is initialized only when the variable is first used.
- A late variable must be nullable, i.e., it must be declared with a `?` to indicate that it could be null.
- A late variable can be a field in a class or a top-level variable.

Here's an example:

```dart
late int myAge;
late List<String> myHobbies;

void main() {
  myAge = 30;
  myHobbies = ['Reading', 'Coding', 'Swimming'];
  print(myAge);
  print(myHobbies);
}
```

In this example, we have declared two variables `myAge` and `myHobbies` using the `late` keyword. These variables are not assigned at the time of declaration but are initialized later in the code. When we try to use these variables before initialization, we will get a runtime error. 

Note: It's important to use `late` with caution as it can introduce null-safety issues if not used correctly.

To access a member variable of a parent class from a child class in Flutter, you need to use the `super` keyword.

Here's an example:

```dart
class ParentClass {
  String parentVariable;

  ParentClass({required this.parentVariable});
}

class ChildClass extends ParentClass {
  String childVariable;

  ChildClass({required String parentVariable, required this.childVariable})
      : super(parentVariable: parentVariable);

  void printParentVariable() {
    print(super.parentVariable);
  }
}

void main() {
  ChildClass myChild = ChildClass(parentVariable: 'Parent', childVariable: 'Child');
  print(myChild.parentVariable); // prints 'Parent'
  print(myChild.childVariable);  // prints 'Child'
  myChild.printParentVariable(); // prints 'Parent'
}
```

In this example, we have a parent class `ParentClass` with a member variable `parentVariable`. We also have a child class `ChildClass` that extends the `ParentClass` and has its own member variable `childVariable`. 

To access the `parentVariable` in the `ChildClass`, we use `super` keyword followed by the name of the variable. In the `ChildClass` constructor, we also use `super` to initialize the parent class constructor with a value of `parentVariable`. 

In the `main` function, we create an object of `ChildClass` and access its `parentVariable` and `childVariable`. We also call `printParentVariable()` method of `ChildClass` that prints the value of `parentVariable`.

Note: The `super` keyword can only be used to access public members of the parent class. If the member variable is private or protected, you cannot access it using `super`.

In Flutter, the `extends` keyword is used to create a new class that is a subclass or child of another class. 

With the `< >` notation, we can define the type of the class we are extending or the parent class. This is called "generic" or "parameterized" class.

Here's an example:

```dart
class MyParentClass<T> {
  T value;
  MyParentClass(this.value);

  void printValue() {
    print('The value is $value');
  }
}

class MyChildClass extends MyParentClass<String> {
  MyChildClass(String value) : super(value);

  void printChildValue() {
    print('The child value is $value');
  }
}

void main() {
  MyChildClass myChild = MyChildClass('Hello, World!');
  myChild.printValue();       // prints 'The value is Hello, World!'
  myChild.printChildValue();  // prints 'The child value is Hello, World!'
}
```

In this example, we have a `MyParentClass` that is parameterized by type T. It has a member variable `value` of type T and a method `printValue()` that prints the `value`. 

We also have a `MyChildClass` that extends `MyParentClass<String>` and has a method `printChildValue()` that prints the `value`. 

In `main()` function, we create an object of the `MyChildClass` and call its methods to print the values.

Note: By parameterizing the parent class, we can define the type of its members and methods. This makes the code more flexible and reusable.

