After carefully investigating the provided HTML and CSS, I have identified the issue causing the catalog items to display under each other. The problem is caused by flex-wrap: wrap; which causes flex items to wrap over to the next line instead of extending the container's width. To fix this, I have made changes to the CSS code related to the .catalog and the .catalog-item classes.

HTML:

```html
<!-- No changes have been made to the HTML -->
```

CSS:

```css
.catalog {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;
  flex-wrap: nowrap;
  overflow: auto;
  margin: 2rem 0;
}

.catalog-item {
  flex: 0 1 auto;
  width: 200px;
  padding: 1rem;
  margin: 1rem;
  background-color: #ADC3AB;
  border-radius: 5px;
  box-shadow: 0 4px 8px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
  text-align: center;
  transition: all 0.3s ease;
}

.catalog::-webkit-scrollbar {
  width: 0.75rem;
}

.catalog::-webkit-scrollbar-thumb {
  background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);
  border-radius: 0.5rem;
}
```

The catalog will now display its contents horizontally, and the items will be shown in a single row. Users can scroll left or right to view the catalog items. Additionally, a scrollbar is added to the catalog section with custom scrollbar properties for WebKit-based browsers.

