Yes, OpenGL provides debug markers that can be set on various GPU objects (such as textures, buffers, shaders, etc.) to aid in debugging and profiling. These markers can be viewed in RenderDoc, as well as other debugging and profiling tools.

To set a debug marker in OpenGL, you can use the `glObjectLabel` function. This function takes a target (such as `GL_TEXTURE`, `GL_BUFFER`, `GL_PROGRAM`, etc.) and an object ID, and sets a string label on the object. Here is the function signature:

```C++
void glObjectLabel(GLenum identifier, GLuint name, GLsizei length, const GLchar *label);
```

The `identifier` parameter specifies the target of the object (such as `GL_TEXTURE`, `GL_BUFFER`, etc.). The `name` parameter specifies the ID of the object (such as the texture ID, buffer ID, etc.). The `length` parameter specifies the length of the label string (excluding the null terminator). Finally, the `label` parameter is a null-terminated string that contains the label to set on the object.

Here is an example of how to set a debug marker on a texture in OpenGL:

```C++
GLuint texture;
glGenTextures(1, &texture);

// Set texture data and parameters...

glObjectLabel(GL_TEXTURE, texture, 0, "My Texture");
```

This sets the label "My Texture" on the texture specified by `texture`.

In addition to `glObjectLabel`, OpenGL also provides other debug markers that can be used to annotate specific sections of code, such as `glPushDebugGroup` and `glPopDebugGroup`. These functions can be used to group multiple markers together, and can also be used to generate hierarchical debug markers.

Here is an example of how to use `glPushDebugGroup` and `glPopDebugGroup` to group multiple debug markers together:

```C++
glPushDebugGroup(GL_DEBUG_SOURCE_APPLICATION, 0, -1, "My Group");

// Set debug markers on various objects...

glPopDebugGroup();
```

This creates a debug group with the label "My Group", and any debug markers set between the `glPushDebugGroup` and `glPopDebugGroup` calls will be associated with this group.

Note that the availability of debug markers depends on the OpenGL implementation and the GPU driver. Some implementations may not support debug markers, or may only support them in certain contexts (such as debug builds). Therefore, it is recommended to check for the availability of debug markers using the `GL_ARB_debug_output` extension, and to only use debug markers for debugging and profiling purposes, rather than relying on them for production code.

