An example of onChange event for select component in React:

```
import React, { useState } from "react";

function SelectComponent() {
  const [selectedOption, setSelectedOption] = useState("");

  const handleOptionChange = (event) => {
    setSelectedOption(event.target.value);
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <select onChange={handleOptionChange} value={selectedOption}>
        <option value="">Select an option</option>
        <option value="option1">Option 1</option>
        <option value="option2">Option 2</option>
        <option value="option3">Option 3</option>
      </select>
    </div>
  );
}

export default SelectComponent;
```

In this example, we have defined a function called `handleOptionChange` which updates the state of `selectedOption` variable whenever the value of the `select` component changes. The `value` attribute of the `select` component is set to the `selectedOption` variable and the `onChange` event is set to the `handleOptionChange` function. 

This allows us to capture the selected option whenever the user makes a change on the select component.

