```
#include "stm32l072xx.h"
#include "stm32l0xx_hal.h"

#define FLASH_PAGE_SIZE 0x800

uint8_t sram_data[2048] = {0}; // SRAM buffer for storing data to be written to flash
uint16_t dma_data[FLASH_PAGE_SIZE/2]; // DMA buffer for storing SRAM data to be written to flash

int main() {
    // initialize SRAM buffer here
    //...

    // initialize HAL
    HAL_Init();

    // enable clock for flash and DMA
    __HAL_RCC_FLASH_CLK_ENABLE();
    __HAL_RCC_DMA1_CLK_ENABLE();

    // erase flash page before writing
    uint32_t page_addr = 0x0807C000; // example address for page 127
    HAL_FLASH_Unlock();
    FLASH_Erase_Sector(FLASH_SECTOR_127, FLASH_VOLTAGE_RANGE_1);
    HAL_FLASH_Lock();

    // copy SRAM data to DMA buffer
    for (uint16_t i = 0; i < FLASH_PAGE_SIZE/2; i++) {
        dma_data[i] = (uint16_t)(sram_data[i*2] | (sram_data[i*2+1] << 8));
    }

    // initialize DMA to transfer SRAM data to flash
    DMA_HandleTypeDef dma_handle;
    dma_handle.Init.Direction = DMA_MEMORY_TO_MEMORY; // DMA transfer direction
    dma_handle.Init.PeriphInc = DMA_PINC_DISABLE; // peripheral increment disabled since we're writing to same address
    dma_handle.Init.MemInc = DMA_MINC_ENABLE; // memory increment enabled to handle multiple flash write operation
    dma_handle.Init.PeriphDataAlignment = DMA_PDATAALIGN_HALFWORD; // peripheral data alignment
    dma_handle.Init.MemDataAlignment = DMA_MDATAALIGN_HALFWORD; // memory data alignment
    dma_handle.Init.Mode = DMA_NORMAL; // DMA transfer mode
    dma_handle.Init.Priority = DMA_PRIORITY_HIGH; // highest priority to ensure fast transfer
    dma_handle.Instance = DMA1_Channel1;
    HAL_DMA_Init(&dma_handle);

    // write SRAM data to flash using DMA
    HAL_FLASH_Unlock();
    HAL_DMA_Start(&dma_handle, (uint32_t)&dma_data, page_addr, FLASH_PAGE_SIZE/2);
    HAL_DMA_PollForTransfer(&dma_handle, HAL_DMA_FULL_TRANSFER, HAL_MAX_DELAY);
    HAL_FLASH_Lock();

    //...
}
```

In this version, we leverage DMA to perform the flash write operation. DMA stands for Direct Memory Access and allows data to be transferred between two endpoints (in this case, SRAM and flash) without CPU intervention. This reduces the overall processing time and increases the overall speed of the write operation. Note that DMA requires a specially allocated buffer that is word aligned to perform the transfer, hence the introduction of the dma_data buffer.

The primary difference between this version and the previous versions is the use of DMA for the flash write operation. Additionally, we added several DMA setup specifications, such as memory and peripheral address alignment, to optimize the transfer rate. Additionally, using HAL_DMA_PollForTransfer function is more efficient than waiting in a loop since it doesn't utilize the CPU, hence reducing the overall processing time of the write operation.

